Video game strategy

Lovdip Singh

Question of interest/goal of the study

We are interested in the effect strategy has on how long players survive playing the computer game.

Read in and inspect the data:

game.df=read.table("strategy.txt",header=TRUE)
game.df$Strategy=as.factor(game.df$Strategy)
plot(Time ~ Strategy,data=game.df)

summaryStats(Time ~ Strategy,data=game.df)
##              Sample Size     Mean Median   Std Dev Midspread
## ActiveHunt            60 18.39000  15.95  7.380361     9.575
## PatrolPursue          60 34.55667  34.00 11.026507    16.675
## Random                60 53.74000  50.75 18.068844    24.325

The mean and median survival time appears to increase depending on the strategies, with the means being 18.4, 34.6 and 54.7 minutes, for ActiveHunt, PatrolPurse and Random, respectively. The variability also increases depending on the mean of the strategy, with ActiveHunt having the least variability and lowest mean and Random having the greatest variability with the greatest mean.

plot(game.fit, which = 1)

normcheck(game.fit)

##                              Estimate   Tukey.L   Tukey.U
## Random  -  ActiveHunt       297.39795 255.74227 345.83791
## Random  -  PatrolPursue     154.76788 133.09594 179.96640
## ActiveHunt  -  PatrolPursue  52.04067  44.75352  60.51372

Log transforming Time aims to remove the relationship between mean and variance between the strategies. The strategies with higher means also tend to have higher variability. Removing this relationship allows the data to conform to the assumption for ANOVA analysis, that the variance of the residuals are more homogenous. The transformation also improves the normality assumption.

Method and Assumption Checks

We wanted to explain survival time in a video game using strategy, a factor with three levels, so we fitted a One-way ANOVA model to these data. The first model fitted was used time as a response variable, this model indicated that the equality of variance assumption was not satisfied. So we logged Time and this model assumption was satisfied, there were no unduly influential points, and all other model assumption seemed satisfied.

Our final model is

\[log(Time_i)=\beta_0 + \beta_1 \times strat.ActiveHunt_i + \beta_2 \times strat.PatrolPursue_i + \beta_3 \times strat.Random_i + \epsilon_i,\]

Where \(strat.x_i\) is 1 if the player uses the strategy \(x\) and \(0\) otherwise, (with \(x \in {ActiveHunt, PatrolPursue, Random}\)), and \(\epsilon_i \sim iid N(0,\sigma^2)\).

Our model explained 62.5% of the variability in the survival times.

Executive Summary

We have evidence that the median survival time between the different strategies are not the same, (P-value \(\approx 0\)). We found that there were significant differences between all combinations for pairs of strategies.

We estimate the median survival time for ActiveHunt strategy to be between 15.6 minutes to 18.7 minutes, 30.0 minutes to 30.9 minutes for PatrolPursue strategy, and 46.5 minutes to 55.6 minutes for Random strategy.

The longest survival time, in general, was obtained by players using the Random strategy. The median survival time for the Random strategy was estimated to be between 255.74% to 345.84% greater than ActiveHunt strategy survival time, and 133.10% to 179.97% greater than PatrolPursue strategy survival time.

The shortest survival time, in general, was obtained by players using the ActiveHunt strategy. The median survival time for the ActiveHunt strategy was estimated to be between 28.92% to 39.10% of the median Random strategy survival time, and 44.75% and 60.51% of the median PatrolPursue survival time.
